When I reflect back on my almost 40 years of life, this is the quote that resonates with me the most currently on accepting my adult life. I have lived what feels like a hundred different versions of myself. 

The young, naive dreamer, so clueless, lost, full of self doubt and trying so hard to matter… to the world. Thinking if the world could just see and love me I could be made whole. This was a frantic season of my life for about 15 years. Climbing, chasing, networking, urgency, FOMO, so scared I would be missed, passed over, forgotten, not good enough to count. So my energy was that of a constant tornado, not to be missed. 

Then I moved into motherhood. A true rebirth. I saw myself through my daughters eyes. I was her world. I didn’t need to be anything other than me. And to give her all my truest love. That’s always been her only request from me. It made me realize I had a lot of broken pieces inside of me that I needed to heal so I could be the truest form of love to her. One by one identifying and taking off all the masks I have accumulated over the years trying to energy match, people please, and be accepted and loved by the external world. These past few years have been the years I learned to accept and love me. Without needing anyone else to agree with me or love me. Big hard growth. 

I’m approaching this new decade, the big 40, and I just want to live in alignment. I don’t want to make a mess of my energy anymore trying to be all the things for all the people. I just want to quietly and powerfully claim who I really am and be that. I don’t need the the world to love me. I just want to effectively do the work I came here to do and impact the people that are meant to connect with me. 

This next season for me is radical acceptance of myself and purpose. And letting that be my hard stop. Moving through the world w all the love I have, no longer being hasty, but instead thoughtful, and honoring my inner guidance. 

So this quote sums me up. I can’t go back and give my younger self the awareness I have now. I had to earn those lessons. But I can take everything I have learned and move forward in the the next, more enlightened version of myself.
